## 📂 Example Snippets

### 1. Geolocation API
```html
<button onclick="getLocation()">Get My Location</button>
<p id="location"></p>
<script>
function getLocation() {
  if (navigator.geolocation) {
    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
  } else {
    document.getElementById("location").innerHTML = "Not supported.";
  }
}
function showPosition(position) {
  document.getElementById("location").innerHTML =
    "Latitude: " + position.coords.latitude +
    "<br>Longitude: " + position.coords.longitude;
}
</script>
```

### 2. Local Storage API
```html
<input type="text" id="username" placeholder="Enter username">
<button onclick="saveData()">Save</button>
<script>
function saveData() {
  const username = document.getElementById("username").value;
  localStorage.setItem("username", username);
}
</script>
```

---

## ⚠️ Considerations
- **Permissions**: Some APIs (like Geolocation, Notifications) require user consent.  
- **Browser Support**: Not all APIs are supported in every browser. Always check compatibility.  
- **Security**: APIs like Storage and Fetch must be used carefully to avoid exposing sensitive data.  

---

## 📌 Quick Takeaway
- **HTML APIs = JavaScript interfaces for browser features.**  
- They make web apps more interactive (maps, storage, graphics, notifications).  
- Widely used APIs include **DOM, Canvas, Geolocation, Storage, Fetch, and Media**.  

